A module that is targeted using require.ensure is loaded asynchronously. That means, it is loaded /after/ the page itself. Imagine you had a jQuery plugin, that you only wanted to load in certain situations, then you would use this. Here is a bit of code that I use to autoload Highlight.JS only when code blocks are there. This allows me to keep the main scriptâ€™s filesize low, but load additional code on-demand.

```
if($("body").find("pre code").length > 0) {
    require.ensure([
        // Should only load the hljs stuff we need...
        "highlight.js",
        // Stylesheet.
        "highlight.js/styles/hybrid.css"
    ], function(hljs){
        hljs.configure({
            tabReplace: Array(5).join(" ")
        });
        $("body").find("pre code").each(function(i,v){
            if($(v).prop("class").match(/language-.+/ig) != null) {
                // The current block has a language- class.
                $(v).addClass("hascode");
                $(v).parent().addClass("hascode");
                hljs.highlightBlock(v);
            }
        });
    });
}
```

whenever you use require.ensure, that module is put into a separate chunk (aka. another file) which is added to the page once the call occurs. That is also why you have to supply a callback. It will only then be called when the async loading is done and the module is ready to be used.

